If the equation $ax^2+20x+7=0$ has only one solution, then the discriminant is 0.  Therefore, $$20^2-4(a)(7)=0.$$Solving for $a$ gives $a=100$.  Substituting this value back into the original equation, we have $100x^2+20x+7=0$.  Using the quadratic formula gives \begin{align*}
x&=\frac{-20\pm\sqrt{20^2-4(100)(7)}}{2(100)}\\
&=\frac{-20}{200}=\boxed{-\frac{1}{10}}.
\end{align*}
